<TEXT>
members of congress are tempering their 
initial support of president bushs decision to attack gen manuel 
antonio noriegas stronghold with concern about the renegade 
dictators elusiveness and a possible long stay in panama for us 
troops 
i can see a scenario whereby the support for this operation 
could turn difficult for the president rep les aspin dwis 
chairman of the house armed services committee told reporters on 
wednesday 
if there is a beginning middle and end to american military 
involvement it is far better than having this thing dragging out 
over weeks and months added sen robert w kasten jr rwis 
in the hours after american forces invaded panama lawmakers 
from both parties endorsed bushs action as the only option left to 
remove suspected drug trafficker noriega and establish a democratic 
government 
president bushs actions were justified based on the changing 
and alarming circumstances of recent weeks in panama said sen 
sam nunn dga chairman of the senate armed services committee 
sen richard lugar rind a senior foreign relations committee 
member called the invasion an overwhelming success because 
democracy has now been inaugurated and installed in panama 
but as the day wore on with reports of americans held captive 
and noriega still a fugitive lawmakers hinted that the us 
action dubbed operation just cause may prove problematic 
noriega continues to elude us and we dont know where he is 
plus the hostage situation thats a very difficult hostage 
situation plus some kind of a continued american presence loss of 
life here and there occasional sniper fire aspin said 
kasten ranking republican on the senate appropriations 
subcommittee on foreign operations stressed the importance of the 
united states withdrawing its army rangers and special forces as 
quickly as possible 
international public opinion in latin america might well turn 
against the united states if there is sustained fighting with 
us troops in uniform and panamanian blood being spilled kasten 
said 
sen charles robb dva emerging from a classified briefing 
conducted by defense and state department officials said its 
fair to say the duration of the operation is of serious concern for 
a good number of people 
but sen john warner rva ranking minority member on the 
senate armed services committee cautioned against imposing a 
schedule on troop withdrawal 
i dont think we should try to impress a time line warner 
said after the briefing 
aspin predicted that some us forces will remain in panama for 
several months possibly a year shoring up the decimated 
panamanian defense forces most of whom served as police custom 
inspectors or in some public safety capacity 
the us presence was likened to the situation in grenada when 
american mps remained for several months after the invasion 
in addition to the concern over the presence of us forces 
lawmakers said interpretation of the panamanian invasion as a major 
achievement was complicated by noriega who remains at large 
the fact that general noriega is unaccounted for means that 
the principle issue is unresolved robb said 
now it is our responsibility to track down the renegade 
general noriega and bring him to the united states where he can be 
tried and punished as the criminal he truly is added sen 
christopher s bond rmo 
aspin said he believes bush will be under some political heat 
if two three days from now we still have not found noriega and 
captured him the wisconsin democrat however cautioned against 
judging the success of the operation on whether noriega is captured 
other lawmakers questioned the invasions impact on us 
relations with central american nations 
i am gravely concerned that this unilateral military 
intervention may do longterm damage to our foreign policy to our 
ability to work with other nations in latin america and to our 
goal of achieving lasting democracy in the region said sen 
edward kennedy dmass a member of the senate armed services 
committee 
