<TEXT>
if the bush administration was counting on a 
quick surgical strike in panama officials can only conclude that 
their surprise military action is off to a rocky start 
while the wisdom of president bushs decision almost certainly 
will be debated at length in congress the massive american 
military force dispatched to panama faces daunting challenges as 
does the new usinstalled panamanian government as it seeks 
acceptance both at home and abroad 
seldom are military operations pulled off without a hitch and 
panama is no exception the invasion dealt the panamanian defense 
forces a severe blow but gen manuel antonio noriega remains on 
the loose the deaths of american soldiers tend to undercut a 
primary goal of the invasion protecting american lives in what 
bushs view was an increasingly unsafe environment in panama 
the 24000 us troops in panama still face the challenge of 
securing control over panama city they also may be confronted with 
the possibility that some americans may be held hostage and that 
armed pronoriega partisans may be able to engage in guerrilla 
warfare 
still the pentagon could take some comfort that organized 
resistance dissolved within hours after the operation began 
wednesday morning 
the acceptance both nationally and internationally of the 
government the united states helped install in panama remains 
uncertain the bush decision will be viewed positively over time if 
panamanians accept president guillermo endara as their leader and 
foreign governments show their approval by dispatching ambassadors 
to panama city 
bush is able to boast perhaps only one unqualified endorsement 
from a foreign leader great britains while the voices from 
latin america have been almost uniformly negative 
at the organization of american states the holdover pronoriega 
envoy was allowed to assume panamas seat wednesday the envoy sent 
by the newly installed government was rebuffed 
things have gone better for bush on the home front with the 
strong bipartisan congressional backing standing in sharp contrast 
to the widespread criticism bush endured following the recent 
disclosure of two highlevel trips to china 
a cable news network poll found public support for the action in 
excess of 90 percent 
and few could argue with the assessment of william j bennett 
the director of national drug control policy who said of noriega 
i think we can safely conclude that this ends his career as a 
drug trafficker hes not running drugs hes not running panama 
hes just running and thats good 
