us ambassador arthur davis 
returned to panama after a sevenmonth absence wednesday and 
declared that neighboring latin american leaders would deep 
down be pleased that us troops ousted gen manuel antonio 
noriega 
but he warned that life in panama would remain dangerous as 
noriega loyalists retaliate 
davis left panama the day after noriega voided elections which 
most observers say he lost to opposition candidates now installed 
by the us action however other latin american countries have 
sharply criticized the united states and have refused to accept the 
new leadership in panama so far 
davis said the position of those leaders was a reflection of 
their many years supporting noninterventionist treatment of their 
region but he said privately they had to be pleased 
i think that deep down that theyre glad to get rid of this 
man he told a heavily guarded press conference at howard air 
base only a pool of reporters from washington was allowed to 
attend 
he expressed concern that noriega supporters would seek revenge 
i think that this is a very difficult time for security 
because of retaliation there will be retaliation davis said 
the returning ambassador said he was bringing an economic 
recovery plan for discussion with panamas new leaders but made no 
promise of us aid except to point out that 700 million in assets 
would be returned as a result of president bushs decision to lift 
economic sanctions 
