<TEXT>
a chinese man jailed after he and his 
pregnant wife entered the united states illegally to flee a forced 
abortion in china hopes a presidential order will bring him freedom 
li jin lins case is one of the first in the nation to test 
president bushs directive that says fear of forced sterilization 
or abortion can be considered as grounds for granting an alien 
political asylum 
the directive though not specifically for chinese was part of 
bushs nov 30 order allowing many chinese citizens to remain in 
the united states indefinitely after the massacre of prodemocracy 
demonstrators in beijing 
li 37 and his wife wang sai zhen fled their hometown of 
fuzhou after she became pregnant with the couples second child 
ms wang had been forced to have several abortions after the 
birth of her first daughter now 10 because chinese law limits 
most families to one child she feared for her health if forced to 
undergo another said patrick wh wesp lis lawyer the daughter 
remains in china with relatives 
the lis entered the united states from canada last march but 
the us immigration and naturalization service caught them in 
albany and returned li 37 to canada ms wang whose age was 
unavailable was allowed to remain because of her advanced 
pregnancy and gave birth to a girl in new york city 
li and his nephew chun kong cheung tried once more to get into 
the united states but border officers found them in the back of a 
tractortrailer at the peace bridge on oct 14 wesp said 
the couple now fears harassment and worse if they should be 
returned to china and their daughter could suffer even though she 
is a us citizen by virtue of her birth here said kathleen rimar 
a lawyer representing them before the ins 
our research indicates that individuals who have had two 
children face sterilization in china rimar said the child 
would never have any advantages in her life she would be cut out 
of schooling any chance at a job 
she said bushs directive doesnt grant people asylum but it 
gives them a better shot if they can prove they would be forced to 
abort or face sterilization she added that it should apply even 
though the lis were caught before the order was issued 
john j ingham acting district director of the ins said the 
lis are the first refugees in the buffalo area to claim asylum 
because of their countrys familyplanning laws rimar and wesp 
said that as far as they know it is the first such case in the 
country 
