<DOCNO> AP891221-0057 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the united states has plenty of plutonium for 
future use in nuclear weapons and the bush administration should 
drop plans to spend 1 billion to expand supplies of the material 
a government advisory panel concludes 
the conclusion published wednesday by a special committee of the 
national research council contradicts the administrations repeated 
assertions to congress that additional capacity to make 
weapongrade plutonium is vital to national security 
the energy department which owns the nations defense nuclear 
materials plants issued a brief statement saying it had not fully 
analyzed the document but would respond in detail within 30 days 
it said the reports recommendations appear to to fully 
consistent with and supportive of actions already taken or 
planned by the department 
former energy secretary john herrington said during the reagan 
administration that the nation is awash in plutonium but his 
successor james d watkins had disavowed the statement watkins 
contends that while current plutonium supplies are adequate more 
capacity will be needed in the coming decade 
the research council said it saw no good reason either to 
produce more virgin plutonium or to increase the capacity for 
processing recycled plutonium from old weapons it also challenged 
watkins plan to build a 600 million plant in idaho that would 
convert reactorgrade plutonium to weapongrade material 
the department of energy should concentrate on making better 
use of existing plutonium processing capacity as required and 
postpone plans to construct additional capabilities the report 
said 
many private arms control groups have long advocated scaling 
back plutonium operations 
this is a certification by a semiofficial body that you dont 
need additional plutonium supplies said david albright senior 
staff scientist of the federation of american scientists 
the report also criticized some aspects of the energy 
departments overall management of the weapons complex which 
includes 17 major plants and laboratories in 12 states 
on the subject of plutonium the report noted that the united 
states already has more than 20000 nuclear weapons 
the plutonium in these devices plus that in the supply chain 
is obviously sufficient to supply a nuclear deterrent of the 
existing size or even greater it said 
official information on nuclear arms materials is classified 
watkins has advocated building a special isotope separation 
plant at the idaho national engineering laboratory near idaho 
falls it would use a new vaporizing technology to convert 
reactorgrade plutonium now stored near richland wash into 
plutonium suitable for use in nuclear weapons 
the scientific panel cited several reasons for scrapping the 
idaho project 
to our knowledge no compelling need for this material has 
been demonstrated its report said 
it also said the idaho facility if built could complicate 
international efforts to limit the spread of nuclear arms the new 
isotope separation technology could be obtained by other countries 
to convert fuel used in civilian nuclear reactors into highgrade 
plutonium needed to build nuclear bombs it said 
john spratt dsc chairman of a special house committee on 
defense nuclear facilities said in a telephone interview that the 
reports conclusion about plutonium supplies combined with 
congressional resistance to adding more capacity make it very 
unlikely that the special isotope separation plant will be built 
the report also said the energy department should drop plans to 
spend 400 million renovating a building at the rocky flats plant 
near denver that recycles scrap plutonium into weaponsgrade 
material 
the research council is an arm of the national academy of 
sciences a congressionally chartered group that conducts special 
research at the request of the government 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

