<TEXT>
farmers are closing out one of the best 
years ever but will be subject to pivotal decisions in 1990 by 
congress and international trade negotiators agriculture secretary 
clayton yeutter said thursday 
yeutter said 1989 income reached nearrecord levels 
agricultural exports have improved and the farmcredit situation 
has eased for both lenders and borrowers 
net farm income will be either at or near a record for 1989 
he said the numbers are not fully determined yet but certainly 
its been a very good year for american agriculture one of the 
best ever 
most questions at yeutters yearend news conference related to 
the uruguay round trade negotations under the general agreement on 
tariffs and trade or gatt those talks are scheduled to conclude a 
year from now 
yeutter was asked if he thought there would be a freer 
international market by 1999 one of the goals sought by us 
negotiators particularly for agricultural products 
my personal assessment is that we have the best chance for 
significant trade liberalization in agriculture that weve 
experienced since the gatt began 40 years ago he replied 
i do believe itll be a freer market 10 years from now than it 
is today and i also believe firmly that that will work to the 
advantage of the american farmer 
other questions related to legislation being drafted by congress 
to succeed the 1985 farm law that expires next year yeutter said 
teams of agriculture department experts are working on plans for 
the 1990 farm bill but did not divulge details 
the united states at the gatt talks has sought a gradual 
reduction and eventual elimination of all tradedistorting 
subsidies and policies but administration officials have adamantly 
insisted that no us programs would be scrapped unless other 
countries did likewise 
though we may want to make some changes in all of these 
programs in the 1990 farm bill because those may be desirable in 
their own right were not going to unilaterally disarm 
internationally in that legislation yeutter said 
so whether were talking about sugar the wheat program or 
any other program i determined that we not forgo any of our 
negotiating leverage in that 1990 legislative debate he said 
but at the same time i am not prepared to accept the arguments 
of any individual industry to the effect that says all changes in 
the program are offlimits 
yeutter who joined president bushs cabinet in january was 
us trade representative in the reagan administration and has been 
in the thick of uruguay round negotiations since they began sept 
20 1986 in punta del esta uruguay 
im always an optimist as you know he said about the final 
push during talks in 1990 but certainly i do not underestimate 
the negotiating challenge it will be significant indeed 
yeutter said it would require an immense amount of effort and 
