<TEXT>
a path of lanterns flickered against 
a granite memorial thursday as grieving relatives and local 
residents marked the first anniversary of the pan am flight 103 
bombing over this scottish town 
the 270 lights one for each victim killed shone in the night 
after local clergymen dedicated the memorial in a 19th century 
graveyard during a day of somber and poignant commemoration 
at least 20 american relatives joined in the services 
culminating in an openair ecumenical gathering at night outside 
the town hall that on dec 21 1988 became a makeshift morgue 
more than onethird of lockerbie 3500 people turned out in 
freezing temperatures to hear the local roman catholic priest 
declare from this disaster there is no complete recovery 
the honest answer is that quite simply life cannot be the 
same again said the rev patrick keegan it has changed we 
have changed 
in the early evening relatives some sobbing packed an 
isolated stone church tundergarth overlooking the field where the 
cockpit fell from the jumbo jet it was blown apart by terrorist 
bomb in a radio cassette player 
earlier about 500 people gathered in biting cold at a simple 
dedication of the memorial in the dryfesdale cemetery one mile 
outside lockerbie 
while this might be a traumatic experience for us the worst 
has already happened said george williams of joppa md his only 
child a 24yearold us army lieutenant was on the flight 
when we go home well feel a whole lot better added 
williams 58 who came with his wife judy 
vapor trailing from two aircraft overhead formed a cross in what 
appeared to be a coincidental tribute 
all 259 people aboard the new yorkbound pan am jet died and 11 
others died on the ground as the jet exploded over this small town 
in southern scotland 
after a year of painstaking investigation the bomber has not 
been identified but suspicion points to an extremist middle east 
terrorist group the popular front for the liberation of 
palestinegeneral command 
as darkness fell an american couple paul and eleanor hudson 
lighted 270 lanterns along a path leading to the memorial and in a 
circle before it their 16yearold daughter melina was aboard 
the flight 
classmates at melinas school the albany academy for girls in 
albany ny made the lanterns which were sandfilled bags with 
candles inside each was inscribed with a dove and the name of a 
victim 
