editors note steven komarow is a member of the pentagon press 
pool covering military operations in panama 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
panamas newly installed leaders met 
with members of the last legislative assembly and other public 
figures under heavy us guard thursday trying to gain control of 
the country and declaring a dusktodawn curfew 
gunshots echoed in the streets outside as president guillermo 
endara and vice presidents ricardo arias calderon and guillermo 
ford presided over the meeting which contained the incongruous 
spectacle of us soldiers in jeans sweatshirts and other civilian 
clothes sprinkled throughout it 
in his speech to an audience of about 200 endara held out an 
olive branch to followers of deposed dictator gen manuel antonio 
noriega 
endara his vice presidents and members of the audience sang 
with special feeling their national anthem and one line in it we 
have finally achieved our victory 
endara ordered a 6 pm to 6 am curfew in hopes of maintaining 
law and order as thousands of looters roamed the streets smashing 
in windows and hauling away goods from virtually every shop in the 
city 
us troops were too busy with snipers and small bands of armed 
noriega loyalists to challenge the looters 
the new government by the accounts of most foreign observers 
overwhelmingly won an election on may 7 but noriega cancelled it 
and continued his rule 
at the time endara and ford were beaten by members of one of 
noriegas dignity battalions units who are still wrecking 
havoc in the aftermath of the us military takeover that started 
early wednesday morning 
two close aides to endara jailed by noriega over a month ago 
and feared by opposition members to have been tortured or killed 
appeared suddenly at the podium at the start of the session and 
were embraced by endara and his two vice presidents to a warm 
ovation 
the two men miguel batista and ivan mojica were spirited away 
by noriegas police and had not been heard from since they were 
freed from a jail by us troops on wednesday 
several people attending the session said they were grateful for 
the us intervention 
the united states is responsible for delivering the dream we 
have had since 1968 said cattleman felix espansona an assembly 
member in 19521956 
we have had a dictatorship for 20 years and now we feel 
liberated 
endara called the new leadership the national reconstruction 
government in a brief speech he made no threats of retaliation 
against followers of noriega now the subject of a nationwide 
manhunt by the us military and with a 1 million reward offered 
by the white house for his capture 
in a bid for unity endara said he would welcome back members of 
noriegas defense forces who can show they support our 
democracy 
vice president ford said it will take some time to restore 
order but us troops should leave the sooner the better 
he also said it is highly important for our country that 
general noriega be caught and be brought to justice 
a top us military official agreed that noriegas capture is 
critical in restoring law and order 
its a problem because as long as you have the head of the 
snake and you have parts of the snakes body and he can make the 
tapes like he did yesterday then youll have some number of 
hardcore loyalists said lt col bill bennett chief of 
contingency operations plans in us southern command 
the endara government strongly backed by president bush met 
amid tight security provided by dozens of us troops who were all 
dressed in civilian clothes 
panamanian politicians did not want to give the impression of 
total dependence on us supports so the soldiers were asked not 
to wear their uniforms several of them told reporters 
looking out of place with their crewcuts and bluejeans they sat 
in the audience to prevent trouble in the national assembly 
building 
while the speeches were being delivered inside the government 
building shots rang out across the street scattering scores of 
looters and curiosity seekers from outside the wroughtiron gates 
around the assembly 
a us officer in charge of security dismissed it as a minor 
incident only some shopkeeper firing shots into the air to scare 
away a looter the officer told a reporter 
government officials said all public offices and buildings would 
be closed for the next two days virtually everything in panama 
has been closed 
since the us attack and it was unclear when they might 
reopen 
the major exception was the panama canal which resumed full 
operations at dawn thursday military officials said dozens of 
cargo ships were offshore awaiting a chance to go through the canal 
the opposition to the american military takeover in the capital 
city was mostly disorganized said bennett but some noriega 
military units remained in the countryside and would have to be 
dealt with 
with the operation more than 30 hours old the us completed 
taking control of the national assembly building demolished 
noriegas former headquarters and took control of other key points 
in the city 
late wednesday soldiers from the 82nd airborne division swept 
through the downtown marriott hotel where some americans were 
trapped 
bennett estimated that some 3000 of the 24000 us troops 
involved in the operations were military police who would be 
taking over police duties formerly carried out by noriegas forces 
their mission will be to reestablish law and order in panama 
city he said 
one of the primary duties will be to identify and hand over 
duties to panamanian police officers who will be loyal to a 
democratic government he said 
as the police units take over downtown attack units would turn 
their attention to routing out the remaining noriega loyalists 
elsewhere a job which would be made easier if noriega is found 
and captured 
without noriega as a rallying point a lot of the units out 
there that have been sitting on the fence will be calling to tell 
us that they will support the democratic government he said 
us officers reported that there was a mortar fired overnight 
near fort clayton a major us military installation but had no 
details of any damage 
they also reported that a special unit seized a 65foot 
panamanian boat near the bridge of the americas spanning the panama 
canal they captured 18 armed men aboard but found no explosives 
