<TEXT>
aviation pioneer dwane wallace who guided 
cessna aircraft co to dominance in the light plane industry died 
thursday he was 78 
he was a shy modest american hero said william wentz 
director of the institute for aviation research at wichita state 
university wallaces alma mater he was happier talking to 
engineers and pilots than he was a bunch of company presidents 
university trustees and such 
wentz credited wallace with being the first to sell 
singleengine aircraft as a tool for businessmen he said wallace 
also was a trailblazer in the transition to allmetal from 
clothcovered planes 
wallace had been hospitalized about six weeks at hca wesley 
medical center the family asked hospital officials not to release 
information about his condition he reportedly had suffered a 
stroke 
until recent months he had remained active supervising his 
business investments and piloting airplanes on trips 
wallace worked briefly as an engineer for walter beech founder 
of beech aircraft corp after graduating from wsu in 1933 he 
assumed control at cessna after his uncle company founder clyde 
cessna was forced to close by the depression 
wallace and his attorney brother dwight reopened the company 
in 1934 in wichita clyde cessna who had started it in 1927 was 
installed as president dwane wallace was general manager 
the first dwane wallace design cessna manufactured the c34 
was a classic monoplane that became world reknowned as the cessna 
airmaster 
in the early years wallace did selling test flying and was 
known occasionally to enter air races when finances were tight to 
meet the payroll with his winnings 
wallace relinquished his board chairmanship at cessna in 1975 
staying on as a 75000 a year consultant and a board member he 
later cut all ties with the company following a dispute with 
current chairman russ meyer his handpicked successor wallace and 
meyer kept silent about the disagreement 
dwane left a legacy at cessna which will continue to have a 
positive effect for many years meyer said he was an extremely 
professional engineer who set high standards throughout the 
company 
wallace is survived by his wife velma a sister four daughters 
and 11 grandchildren 
</TEXT>
