in the spirit of christmas 8yearold 
carly bores is giving a gift that may mean a longer life for other 
children with cancer 
carly a blueeyed redhaired secondgrader has cancer of the 
lymph system she volunteered through marshfield clinic for an 
international study to test new treatments for cancers in children 
and infants 
when doctors discussed with mike and laura bores their 
daughters hodgkins disease it convinced them to let carly take 
part in the study 
all they can tell us is she has an 85 percent chance of being 
diseasefree for two years mrs bores said they cant say 10 
years or 20 years or a lifetime because they dont have those kinds 
of records 
the more information they can gather from more people the 
easier it will be to tell parents things like that in the future 
carlys ordeal also has changed the meaning of christmas for the 
family 
this christmas the kids will be seeing less under the tree 
and more of me i need to give more of myself mrs bores said 
sitting in a special home on the clinic campus where parents and 
children can live while a child receives radiation treatment the 
familys medical bills total 30000 most of wich has been covered 
by insurance 
the childrens cancer study group headquartered at the 
university of southern california school of medicine in pasadena 
enrolls 6000 patients each year and has 25000 in longterm 
research said dr john weiner administrative director more than 
100 hospitals including 32 major medical centers take par in 
ccsg which was founded in 1955 
all treatments are assigned by the national headquarters which 
also monitors patient progess and evaluates the effectiveness of 
new treatments weiner said adding that the research has led to 
dramatic progress in finding a cure for childhood cancers in 1972 
30 percent of youths with lymphatic cancers lived more two years 
the survival rate is now 80 percent 
if we had the perfect treatment in hand today we wouldnt 
stop these clinical trials for another 10 years he said 
the risk to patients is low weiner said they either receive an 
established treatment with proven results or they may get a better 
treatment with the new drug or therapy being studied 
carly found out in may she had hodgkins disease doctors dont 
know what caused it other than a cell decided to divide wrong 
said mrs bores who with her husband mike owns an outdoors 
sports store in three lakes 
the couple have one other child 10yearold aaron 
after 12 drug treatments carly started radiation therapy in 
early december for the next two years she will undergo monthly 
xrays and blood tests to make sure the cancer is destroyed 
because her spleen was removed she also must take penicillin every 
day for the rest of her life 
usually if a second cancer occurs it is within the first two 
years the longer you go past that twoyear mark the better your 
prognosis is said mrs bores adding that the shock of finding 
out her child had cancer has made her more patient more flexible 
and probably kinder this holiday season i feel so fortunate that 
i can take carly and hug her and love her 
as for carly she says the most difficult part of her ordeal was 
the surgery when a catheter was installed for chemotherapy she 
knows how serious the disease is because a friend died of hodgkins 
disease two years ago 
but this is christmastime and shes been getting ready as 
though her life hasnt changed at all theres been cookies to 
bake shopping to do and the excitement of hoping she may get more 
coins for her collection 
its the same as last year she said christmas is 
christmas 
