<TEXT>
a proposal by the european economic community 
to overhaul agricultural trade will clear the way for final 
negotiations with the eec in 1990 the bush administration said 
this is the last of the major proposals to be submitted and 
now will permit the final negotiations on agriculture to get under 
way early next year said us trade representative carla hills 
and agriculture secretary clayton yeutter 
however they added in a joint statement wednesday certain 
aspects of the eec proposal cannot be accepted by the united states 
the comprehensive eec proposal was made in geneva in the uruguay 
round of trade talks under the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade the gatt negotiations are scheduled to conclude at the end 
of 1990 
while the proposal contains some positive indications we are 
concerned with the continued reliance by the eec on managed 
agriculture and in particular the apparent intention to continue 
to rely upon largescale subsidies and especially export 
subsidies the leaders said 
government programs that manage markets are one of the major 
causes of the current trade distortions in agriculture they 
said the successful future of trade in agriculture depends on 
market liberalization and significant reduction of subsidies that 
distort trade 
the united states cannot accept the eec proposal to 
rebalance import protection mrs hills and yeutter said 
rebalancing would raise tariffs reduce market access and 
increase the price of food to consumers they said rebalancing 
is simply protectionism by another name and we believe the other 
gatt countries will recognize it as such 
mrs hills and yeutter said the eec approach does little to 
liberalize market access and that the 12nation blocs position 
on export subsidies is unacceptably weak and totally out of 
step with other proposals made in the talks 
