<DOCNO> AP891221-0239 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the 12 european economic community 
nations on thursday adopted a law that gives the eec veto power 
over large mergers within the trade bloc 
ministers of the common market countries granted the eecs 
administrative arm the european commission authority over mergers 
that currently rests with the governments of the 12 members 
under the new law any proposed merger within the eec that would 
create a company with worldwide revenue of more than 585 billion 
must be approved by the commission 
the law also requires that the commission review a merger 
creating a firm with revenue inside the eec of more than 2925 
million 
transactions valued at amounts under the ceilings approved 
thursday would come under the jurisdiction of individual eec 
members 
the law applies to mergers between two eec companies as well as 
to deals where only one company is an eec firm 
before the law was passed most large mergers were already being 
submitted to the commission to ensure that proposed combinations 
did not violate eec competition rules 
under the law the commission would be allowed to base its 
judgment primarily on the effect a proposed merger would have on 
competition within the eec a narrow standard pushed by britain 
in some cases however the commission will take into account 
the effects of a merger on individual national markets 
the vote ended 16 years of negotiations to bring mergers under 
eec control the agreement was seen as a victory for the french 
government which currently holds the sixmonth rotating eec 
presidency and had set an agreement on the merger law as one of its 
goals 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

