<TEXT>
consumer spending rebounded 07 percent in 
november from its sharp fall a month earlier the government 
reported thursday and analysts said it continues to be one of the 
bright spots in a slowing economy 
it suggests that while we have some weak areas in the economy 
particularly in the manufacturing sector that the consumer has not 
turned off completely said david jones an economist with aubrey 
g lanston amp co in new york 
the commerce department also reported an 08 percent increase in 
personal incomes in november but some analysts questioned whether 
income growth will soon begin to weaken and thus cause a decline in 
spending 
the report said consumer spending rose at a seasonally adjusted 
annual rate to 354 trillion a 07 percent increase and the 
steepest gain since a 1 percent jump last april 
the advance was a rebound from a 02 percent decline in october 
which was the first decrease since a 01 percent dip in september 
1988 and the largest drop since a 14 percent fall in january 1987 
consumer spending which has been a major factor for the 
economic growth during the first nine months of the year is 
watched closely as a barometer of economic health because it 
accounts for about twothirds of the nations economic activity 
commerce reported last week that retail sales rose 08 percent 
in november a rebound from a 13 percent decrease in october 
analysts said it reflected the start of the christmas buying season 
the weekend after thanksgiving 
as measured by the gross national product the economy grew at a 
3 percent rate in the third quarter after gains of 37 percent in 
the first and 25 percent in the second but analysts expect a 
sharp decline in the threemonth period ending dec 31 
jones said prospects are good for continued consumer spending 
particularly in nondurables such as apparel and in the services 
area because consumers are still basically optimistic and have 
income growth to support that optimism 
personal incomes in november totaled 454 trillion at a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate following a similar 08 percent 
gain to 450 trillion in october it was the largest increase 
since a 1 percent gain last march 
but lawrence chimerine senior economic adviser for the wefa 
group a bala cynwyd pa forecasting group said there were a 
number of factors that could lead to decreased spending 
the negatives are the high debt loads he said people now 
are getting more concerned about the future youre seeing more 
layoffs and particularly for durables the pentup demand we had 
in the earlier 80s has just been used up people just dont have 
the same needs 
the 262 billion increase in personal consumption which 
includes everything except interest payments on debt contrasted to 
a 63 billion decrease in october 
purchases of durable goods bigticket items expected to last 
more than three years rose 19 billion while purchases of 
nondurable goods jumped 124 billion spending on services 
increased 119 billion 
the november report showed that americans incomes after taxes 
rose 09 percent up from octobers 08 percent gain 
americans savings rate savings as a percent of disposable 
income rose to 61 percent up from octobers 57 percent rate 
the key component of the income category wages and salaries 
edged up 17 billion in november following a 294 billion gain in 
october 
payrolls at manufacturing companies hit hardest by the federal 
reserves highinterest polices fell 49 billion after an 
october advance of 63 billion 
